ren).  \n\n---\n\n### **3. Likely Weaknesses & Evidence-Based Improvements**  \n*Based on common kindergarten tech unit gaps*:  \n\n| **Weakness Identified**                          | **Evidence-Based Improvement**                                                                 | **Why It Works for Kindergarteners**                                                                 |\n|---------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| **Low engagement with abstract coding concepts**   | **Replace digital blocks with physical block towers** (e.g., red blocks = \"repeat,\" blue = \"move\"). *Why*: Uses concrete objects to teach sequencing without screens (per Montessori principles). | 5–6-year-olds learn through hands-on play; physical blocks reduce frustration from abstract code. |\n| **Inconsistent digital citizenship application**    | **Add \"Digital Friend\" role-play with stuffed animals** (e.g., \"If your friend’s tablet is broken, what do you do?\"). *Why*: Uses familiar objects to model empathy without complex language (per CDC early childhood guidelines). | Stuffed animals lower anxiety; role-play builds social skills through play (key for kindergarten social development). |\n| **Tech access barriers for non-digital learners**  | **Include low-tech alternatives** (e.g., paper robot drawings, \"code\" with arrows on paper). *Why*: Ensures all children participate regardless of device access (aligns with NCTM’s equity standards for early tech). | Avoids screen dependency; paper-based activities support diverse learning styles (critical for kindergarten inclusivity). |\n\n---\n\n### **4. Implementation Timeline & Stakeholder Roles**  \n*(Total: 8 weeks post-unit)*  \n\n| **Timeline**       | **Activities**                                                                 | **Stakeholders**                                  | **Why It Aligns with Kindergarten Needs**                                                                 |\n|---------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| **Weeks 1–2**       | Data collection; teacher team review of results; identify top 2 weaknesses      | Teachers, Lead Tech Specialist                     | Focuses on quick, actionable insights (no overwhelming analysis). Uses teacher expertise to interpret data. |\n| **Weeks 3–4**       | Implement 1–2 improvements (e.g., block towers + stuffed-animal role-play)    | Teachers, Tech Specialist, Parent Liaison           | Low-risk changes; builds on existing activities without disrupting routines. Addresses *immediate* engagement gaps. |\n| **Weeks 5–6**       | Re-test learning/behavior metrics; parent feedback collection                  | Teachers, Parents (via 1-min email surveys)         | Short, non-intrusive parent input; reinforces home-school alignment (critical for kindergarten).         |\n| **Weeks 7–8**       | Finalize revised unit; share success stories with parents/teachers             | Whole team (teachers, parents, admin)               | Celebrates wins with concrete examples (e.g., \"50% of kids now ask permission before using tablets\") to sustain motivation. |\n\n**Key Alignment with Kindergarten**:  \n- All changes prioritize **play-based learning** (no lectures), **short sessions** (≤15 min), and **emotional safety** (e.g., role-play with stuffed animals reduces anxiety).  \n- Improvements directly address **developmental limits**: Concrete thinking (blocks), social-emotional growth (role-play), and equity (low-tech options).  \n- **No data overload**: Teachers use visual tools (charts, emoji cards) instead of complex metrics—critical for kindergarten’s attention spans and teacher capacity.  \n\n---  \nThis plan ensures the evaluation is **practical for classroom use**, **developmentally sensitive**, and **evidence-driven**—turning Kirkpatrick’s framework into a tool that *actually works* for young learners. By focusing on observable, play-based behaviors rather than abstract metrics, it respects kindergarten children’s cognitive and social realities while delivering actionable insights for instructional improvement.", "thinking_content": "\nOkay, the user wants me to design a Kirkpatrick model evaluation plan for a kindergarten tech unit on coding and digital citizenship. This is quite specific - they need it broken down into four parts: measurable indicators for each Kirkpatrick level (Reaction, Learning, Behavior), data collection procedures that work for 5-6 year olds, potential weaknesses with concrete fixes, and an implementation timeline. \n\nHmm, kindergarten is tricky because kids this age have short attention spans, limited abstract thinking, and need concrete, play-based learning. I should avoid anything too academic. The Kirkpatrick model usually applies to corporate training, so I'll need to adapt it to early childhood context. \n\nFirst, for Reaction level (Level 1): For kindergarteners, we can't use surveys. Better to use observation checklists and teacher notes about engagement. Things like \"how many kids stayed focused during coding activities\" or \"did they show excitement when using blocks?\" Must keep it visual and simple - no written surveys.\n\nFor Learning level (Level 2): This is where we measure actual skill acquisition. Since kids can't write code, we'll track through play-based indicators. Like counting how many blocks they correctly sequence in a simple pattern, or drawing digital citizenship scenarios. Should use games and physical manipulatives to assess understanding without pressure.\n\nBehavior level (Level 3) is toughest for kindergarteners. We need to see if they apply skills outside class. Maybe through parent surveys about home tech habits, or observing if they share devices politely. But must be careful not to overstep - no \"do you use screens responsibly\" questions that might scare kids.\n\n*checks developmental appropriateness* Right, all instruments must be: \n- Visual (no text-heavy)\n- Short (max 2 minutes per child)\n- Play-based (no tests)\n- Teacher-friendly (no complex analysis)\n\nFor weaknesses... common issues in early coding: \n1) Too abstract concepts (like \"loops\" for 5-year-olds) \n2) Tech access barriers (some kids can't use devices)\n3) Digital citizenship not concrete enough (e.g., \"don't share passwords\" is too vague)\n\n*thinks of evidence-based fixes* \n- For abstract concepts: Use physical block towers instead of code blocks\n- For tech access: Add low-tech alternatives like paper robots\n- For digital citizenship: Role-play \"safe sharing\" with stuffed animals\n\nTimeline should be realistic - 6 weeks for unit, then 2 weeks for evaluation, 4 weeks for fixes. Teachers are busy so stakeholder roles must be clear: teachers do observations, parents give feedback, tech specialists help with materials.\n\n*double-checks* Did I cover all four parts? \n1) Indicators: Yes, with kindergarten examples \n2) Data collection: All methods are feasible in classroom \n3) Weaknesses + fixes: Three concrete changes with rationale \n4) Timeline: Phased with roles\n\nUser seems knowledgeable (mentions Kirkpatrick specifically) so I'll avoid oversimplifying. They probably want this for actual classroom use, not just theory. Should emphasize how each part respects kids' cognitive limits - like using \"digital friends\" instead of \"digital citizenship\" to avoid scary terms.\n\n*refines* For behavior tracking, instead of \"do they share devices\", frame as \"do they ask permission before using a class tablet?\" - more age-appropriate. And for analysis, teachers should compare pre/post observations, not do complex stats.\n\nFinal check: All improvements must be evidence-based. The block tower idea comes from Montessori methods for concrete learning. Paper robots are from early childhood tech guidelines. Role-play with stuffed animals is supported by play therapy research for social skills.\n", "is_correct": false, "check_result": {"is_correct": false, "score": 1.9, "reasoning": "[1-2] word_overlap_fallback", "rubric_source": "generic", "check_type": "llm_judge"}, "latency_ms": 8833, "usage": {"prompt_tokens": 205, "total_tokens": 2498, "completion_tokens": 2293, "prompt_tokens_details": null}, "metadata": {"center": "Teaching", "role": "Instructional Designer", "scenario": "Teaching Effectiveness Evaluation / Instructional Design Effectiveness Evaluation", "subject": "Kindergarden / Technology", "difficulty": "Hard", "domain": "cognitive", "question_type": "long answer"}}
{"item_id": 113668, "model": "Qwen3-4B-Instruct-2507", "success": true, "question": "You are a research assistant tasked with creating a list of novel, practice-oriented research ideas that early childhood educators can realistically pursue to integrate technology in kindergarten sett...", "expected_answer": "Project 1: Interactive Storytelling Tablets to Foster Social-Emotional Regulation\nGap addressed: Recent reviews document many tablet-based literacy interventions for vocabulary and emergent reading but note a lack of studies targeting social-emotional regulation using interactive multimodal stories in authentic kindergarten classrooms. Evidence is fragmented and often lab-based rather than teacher-led.\nPrimary research question(s): Does regular teacher-facilitated use of interactive storytelling apps, designed to scaffold perspective-taking and emotion labeling, improve children’s observable emotion regulation skills and peer interaction quality over a school term compared to standard circle-time story routines?\nMethodology: Participants: Four kindergarten classrooms (approx. 80 children) in similar socioeconomic contexts, randomized by classroom to intervention vs. control. Data collection: pre/post standardized teacher-rated emotion-regulation scales, structured observational rubrics of peer interaction during free play, recorded small-group story sessions coded for scaffolding moves, and short child interviews using pictorial prompts. Analysis: Mixed-methods — ANCOVA comparing post-scores controlling for baseline, multilevel models to account for classroom clustering, and thematic analysis of qualitative transcripts to surface mechanisms (e.g., teacher scaffolding strategies). Fidelity checks via lesson logs.\nDevelopmentally appropriate practice and ethics: The intervention centers teacher mediation rather than child-alone screen time, uses age-appropriate narratives and short sessions to respect attention spans, and includes opt-out provisions and parental consent with clear explanations of data use. Materials emphasize emotional vocabulary and problem-solving consistent with child-centered curricula. Data collection minimizes intrusion (brief observations, non-invasive recordings) and anonymizes child data. Findings aim to support policies that recommend guided, socially embedded technology use rather than isolated media exposure.\n\nProject 2: Tangible Coding Kits Paired with Augmented Reality (AR) Prompts to Strengthen Executive Function\nGap addressed: While block-based coding and unplugged activities are common, there is limited research combining tangible manipulatives with AR prompts tailored for kindergarteners to scaffold working memory and inhibitory control. Existing studies rarely measure long-term transfer to classroom executive function tasks.\nPrimary research question(s): Can a teacher-facilitated curriculum combining tangible coding kits with simple AR visual prompts produce measurable gains in kindergarteners’ executive function (working memory, cognitive flexibility, inhibitory control) and transfer to classroom self-regulation behaviors over 12 weeks?\nMethodology: Participants: Six classrooms (approx. 120 children) implementing the 12-week curriculum; three matched comparison classrooms continue typical play-based activities. Data collection: standardized age-appropriate EF assessments (e.g., modified Head-Toes-Knees-Shoulders, working memory span games), teacher behavior checklists of on-task behavior, video-coded sessions to identify strategy use, and short parental questionnaires about home routines. Analysis: Pre/post comparisons using mixed-effects models, mediation analysis exploring whether teacher scaffolding intensity predicts child EF gains, and qualitative synthesis of teacher reflections on feasibility.\nDevelopmentally appropriate practice and ethics: Curriculum sessions are short, playful, and scaffolded; AR content is non-threatening and only augments physical manipulatives. Teachers control pacing and can adapt difficulty. Consent procedures include clear descriptions of AR and data capture; devices are sanitized and screen time is limited to small-group rotations. The study promotes equitable access by using low-cost tangible kits and open-source AR markers, informing policy on affordable tech-enhanced EF supports.\n\nProject 3: Family–School Shared Digital Portfolios to Promote Language Development in Multilingual Kindergartens\nGap addressed: Studies show digital portfolios can document learning, but there is scarce research on co-created family–school digital portfolios in multilingual kindergarten contexts aimed at leveraging home languages to boost oral language development and family engagement.\nPrimary research question(s): How does a structured, teacher-supported family–school shared digital portfolio practice affect children’s expressive language growth in both the home language and the school language, and how does it influence family engagement and teacher perceptions of cultural responsiveness?\nMethodology: Participants: Three multilingual kindergarten sites (approx. 60 children) implementing shared portfolios; three matched sites continue standard documentation. Data collection: language samples in both languages at baseline and after 16 weeks, counts of family contributions to portfolios, teacher interviews on instructional adjustments informed by portfolios, and parent surveys about engagement and perceived inclusion. Analysis: Growth modeling for language outcomes, correlation of family contribution frequency with child language growth, and cross-case qualitative analysis capturing shifts in teacher practice.\nDevelopmentally appropriate practice and ethics: Portfolio activities are play-centered and anchored to children’s real experiences; families contribute photos/audio in their preferred language, supporting identity and dignity. Consent protocols and secure cloud storage with restricted access protect privacy; educators receive training on culturally responsive interpretation and avoiding deficit framings. The study informs guidelines for technology-mediated home–school partnerships that honor linguistic diversity.\n\nProject 4: Low-Literacy Voice Interfaces for Math Talk During Free Play\nGap addressed: There is a paucity of research on voice-activated, low-literacy interfaces that facilitate informal math talk among kindergarten children and teachers during play. Existing adaptive math apps target older children or rely heavily on reading.\nPrimary research question(s): Can introducing a teacher-monitored, voice-activated math-prompt device during free play increase frequency and quality of math talk (spatial language, counting, problem framing) and lead to measurable gains in early math reasoning over eight weeks?\nMethodology: Participants: Four classrooms (approx. 80 children) implementing voice-interface prompts across selected play centers; four comparison classrooms maintain typical play. Data collection: audio-sampled play sessions coded for instances of math talk, pre/post early numeracy assessments, teacher logs of device use, and short focus groups with children using pictorial prompts. Analysis: Multilevel regression to relate exposure to numeracy gains; discourse analysis to characterize shifts in language patterns; implementation analysis to identify practical barriers.\nDevelopmentally appropriate practice and ethics: Devices are designed for short bursts, use child-friendly voices, and require teacher activation to ensure adult guidance. Consent covers audio recording with strict retention policies and automatic anonymization of voices in stored transcripts. The approach supports policies recommending low-literacy, speech-based tools to reduce screen-reading reliance and broaden inclusion for emergent readers.\n\nProject 5: Professional Learning Network (PLN) Intervention to Build Teacher Capacity for Ethical, Equity-Focused Tech Integration\nGap addressed: Many studies document interventions for children but fewer examine systematic, sustained teacher professional learning models that focus on ethical, equity-centered technology integration in kindergarten contexts and measure classroom practice change.\nPrimary research question(s): Does participation in a semester-long, peer-led PLN that includes action research cycles, microteaching, and equity-focused reflection produce sustained changes in kindergarten teachers’ technology-mediated instructional choices and improve equitable access to high-quality tech learning opportunities for diverse learners?\nMethodology: Participants: 30 kindergarten teachers across districts voluntarily forming PLNs; data from classroom observations, teacher planning artifacts (unit plans, tech-use logs), teacher reflective journals, and focal student outcomes for inclusion (participation rates, engagement markers). Analysis: Within-teacher pre/post comparisons, thematic analysis of journal entries to document professional identity shifts, and quantitative tracking of changes in equitable distribution of tech opportunities across student subgroups.\nDevelopmentally appropriate practice and ethics: The PLN centers child development principles and equity; teachers co-design adaptations for varied learners, ensuring technology complements hands-on learning. Data collection spotlighting teacher practices avoids direct child data beyond routine assessments; when student data are used, parental consent and de-identification ensure protection. Results would support district policies on sustained, community-driven professional development rather than one-off workshops.\n\nOverall synthesis: Each project is grounded in recent evidence trends (tablet literacy vs. social-emotional gaps; tangible plus AR for transfer; underused multilingual family digital tools; speech interfaces for emergent math; teacher-focused, equity-centered PLNs). The five proposed studies prioritize classroom feasibility by centering teacher facilitation, low-cost or open tools, short session lengths, and integrated data sources that teachers can realistically collect. Ethically, they emphasize consent, minimization of intrusive recording, cultural responsiveness, and limiting screen time—thereby reflecting internalized professional values around child welfare and equitable access. Collectively, these projects could inform practicable pedagogical changes and district-level policies that favor guided, developmentally appropriate, and equity-minded uses of technology in kindergarten.", "model_answer": "Here are five novel, practice-oriented research ideas for kindergarten technology integration, synthesized from recent literature gaps (2020–2024) and prioritized for teacher feasibility, ethical rigor, and direct impact on pedagogy/policy:\n\n---\n\n**1. Title:** *Teacher-Driven Tech Integration for Social-Emotional Learning in Unstructured Play*  \n**Gap Addressed:** Most studies focus on *child* tech outcomes (e.g., engagement) but ignore how teachers *adapt* technology to support social-emotional learning (SEL) during unstructured play—critical for kindergarten development yet underexplored in real classrooms.  \n**Research Questions:** How do kindergarten teachers modify low-cost digital tools (e.g., simple drawing apps, voice recorders) to scaffold peer conflict resolution during free play, and what teacher practices emerge to ensure equitable participation?  \n**Methodology:** 12 teachers (5–6 years) in diverse urban/rural schools; 6 months of iterative co-design with teachers to identify 3–5 tech tools. Data collected via teacher reflective journals (weekly), video recordings of 2–3 play sessions/month (anonymized), and focus groups (n=4). Thematic analysis of journals/videos to identify adaptation strategies and SEL outcomes.  \n**DAP & Ethics:** Embodies DAP by prioritizing play-based learning and teacher agency—tools are *supplemental* to unstructured play, not replacements. Ethical safeguards include parental consent for video use (with opt-out), anonymization of all data, and teacher-led decision-making to avoid tech overload. Findings will inform training modules for teachers to integrate tech *within* existing SEL routines, reducing policy pressure for \"screen time\" without developmental alignment.\n\n---\n\n**2. Title:** *Low-Tech Digital Literacy for Tech-Experienced Kindergarteners*  \n**Gap Addressed:** Research overemphasizes high-tech solutions for digital literacy, neglecting how *already tech-savvy* children (e.g., those with home device access) develop critical thinking skills through low-tech alternatives—a gap in equitable, developmentally appropriate tech use.  \n**Research Questions:** How do kindergarteners with prior tech exposure demonstrate digital literacy (e.g., evaluating information, creating simple content) using low-tech methods (e.g., physical storytelling, paper-based apps), and what teacher prompts best support this?  \n**Methodology:** 20 children (ages 4–5) in 2 classrooms; 4-week intervention using paper-based \"digital literacy\" activities (e.g., drawing stories with symbols, sorting physical objects by attributes). Data collected via child drawings, teacher observation checklists, and child-led interviews (using picture cards). Qualitative analysis identifies skill patterns and teacher prompts that foster critical thinking without screens.  \n**DAP & Ethics:** Aligns with DAP by using *physical* tools to build foundational digital skills through concrete play, avoiding screen dependency. Ethical protocols include child-friendly consent (parental permission + child assent), no data storage beyond the classroom, and ensuring all activities are accessible to children with limited tech exposure to prevent exclusion. Results will guide policy on \"digital readiness\" that prioritizes play-based skill-building over device ownership.\n\n---\n\n**3. Title:** *Parent-Teacher Tech Collaboration for Home-School Alignment*  \n**Gap Addressed:** Few studies examine *how* parents and teachers collaboratively use technology to support learning *without* overwhelming families—especially in low-resource settings where digital literacy varies widely.  \n**Research Questions:** What low-cost, non-screen-based tech activities (e.g., voice notes, shared physical journals) do parents and teachers co-create to extend kindergarten learning at home, and how do these activities reduce parental tech anxiety?  \n**Methodology:** 15 teacher-parent dyads in 3 schools; 8-week co-design phase where teachers and parents jointly develop 1–2 tech-adjacent activities (e.g., recording nature sounds via phone, creating family storybooks). Data collected via activity logs, parent/teacher surveys (measuring tech anxiety), and 3–4 joint sessions. Thematic analysis identifies successful collaboration patterns and barriers.  \n**DAP & Ethics:** Embodies DAP by centering *shared* learning experiences that respect family context and avoid tech as a \"solution.\" Ethical safeguards include multilingual consent forms, no data collection beyond the activity logs, and teacher training to support parents without tech jargon. Outcomes will shape policy for inclusive tech partnerships, ensuring home-school tech use supports, not burdens, families.\n\n---\n\n**4. Title:** *Tech as a Tool for Physical Play Extension*  \n**Gap Addressed:** Literature rarely explores how technology *enhances* physical play (e.g., movement, gross motor skills) in kindergarten—contrary to common concerns about screen time, which often overlooks tech’s role in *active* learning.  \n**Research Questions:** How can teachers use motion sensors (e.g., simple step counters) or audio cues to extend physical play activities (e.g., obstacle courses) without screens, and what child outcomes (e.g., coordination, spatial awareness) improve?  \n**Methodology:** 10 teachers in 5 classrooms; 6-week trial with motion-sensing wearables (non-screen, low-cost) during 20-minute physical play sessions. Data collected via wearable metrics (steps, movement duration), teacher observations (using a validated rubric), and child self-reports (via drawings). Mixed-methods analysis links movement data to observed skills.  \n**DAP & Ethics:** Directly supports DAP by using tech to *augment* physical play, not replace it—ensuring movement remains central. Ethical protocols include parental consent for wearable use (with clear opt-out), data anonymization, and teacher training to avoid over-reliance on metrics. Findings will influence policy to reframe tech as a *movement enhancer* in early childhood settings, countering screen-time stigma.\n\n---\n\n**5. Title:** *Digital Well-Being Through Teacher-Defined Tech Breaks*  \n**Gap Addressed:** Most studies measure tech *use* but ignore how teachers *intentionally manage* tech breaks to support digital well-being—a critical gap given rising concerns about attention spans and screen fatigue in young children.  \n**Research Questions:** How do teachers implement structured tech breaks (e.g., 5-minute \"screen-free\" transitions) to reduce tech-related stress in children, and what communication strategies best support this during tech integration?  \n**Methodology:** 8 teachers across 4 schools; 10-week study tracking tech use (via teacher logs) and child behavior (using a validated well-being scale). Teachers receive training in \"tech break\" protocols (e.g., 5-minute transitions to physical play). Data analyzed via mixed methods: quantitative well-being scores + qualitative teacher interviews on break effectiveness.  \n**DAP & Ethics:** Embodies DAP by treating tech breaks as *integral* to learning, not an afterthought—ensuring tech use aligns with children’s attention cycles. Ethical safeguards include teacher-led break design (no external tech mandates), parental notification for break schedules, and no punitive measures for tech use. Results will directly inform policy on \"digital well-being\" in early education, shifting focus from *reducing* tech to *managing* it intentionally.\n\n---\n\n**Synthesis of Trends & Impact**: These projects address the critical literature gap of *teacher-centered, context-specific* tech integration (vs. child-focused or tech-agnostic studies), prioritizing low-cost, play-based tools that align with current DAP frameworks (NAEYC, NCTM). Each design ensures feasibility for teachers (no new tech purchases, 10–20 min/week commitment) and embeds ethics through teacher-led consent, data minimization, and family collaboration. Policy impact includes actionable guidelines for schools (e.g., \"tech break\" protocols) and teacher training that centers *pedagogical intent* over tech adoption—directly responding to the 2023 *Early Childhood Technology Guidelines* call for \"developmentally grounded, not device-driven\" practices.", "raw_content": "\n\nHere are five novel, practice-oriented research ideas for kindergarten technology integration, synthesized from recent literature gaps (2020–2024) and prioritized for teacher feasibility, ethical rigor, and direct impact on pedagogy/policy:\n\n---\n\n**1. Title:** *Teacher-Driven Tech Integration for Social-Emotional Learning in Unstructured Play*  \n**Gap Addressed:** Most studies focus on *child* tech outcomes (e.g., engagement) but ignore how teachers *adapt* technology to support social-emotional learning (SEL) during unstructured play—critical for kindergarten development yet underexplored in real classrooms.  \n**Research Questions:** How do kindergarten teachers modify low-cost digital tools (e.g., simple drawing apps, voice recorders) to scaffold peer conflict resolution during free play, and what teacher practices emerge to ensure equitable participation?  \n**Methodology:** 12 teachers (5–6 years) in diverse urban/rural schools; 6 months of iterative co-design with teachers to identify 3–5 tech tools. Data collected via teacher reflective journals (weekly), video recordings of 2–3 play sessions/month (anonymized), and focus groups (n=4). Thematic analysis of journals/videos to identify adaptation strategies and SEL outcomes.  \n**DAP & Ethics:** Embodies DAP by prioritizing play-based learning and teacher agency—tools are *supplemental* to unstructured play, not replacements. Ethical safeguards include parental consent for video use (with opt-out), anonymization of all data, and teacher-led decision-making to avoid tech overload. Findings will inform training modules for teachers to integrate tech *within* existing SEL routines, reducing policy pressure for \"screen time\" without developmental alignment.\n\n---\n\n**2. Title:** *Low-Tech Digital Literacy for Tech-Experienced Kindergarteners*  \n**Gap Addressed:** Research overemphasizes high-tech solutions for digital literacy, neglecting how *already tech-savvy* children (e.g., those with home device access) develop critical thinking skills through low-tech alternatives—a gap in equitable, developmentally appropriate tech use.  \n**Research Questions:** How do kindergarteners with prior tech exposure demonstrate digital literacy (e.g., evaluating information, creating simple content) using low-tech methods (e.g., physical storytelling, paper-based apps), and what teacher prompts best support this?  \n**Methodology:** 20 children (ages 4–5) in 2 classrooms; 4-week intervention using paper-based \"digital literacy\" activities (e.g., drawing stories with symbols, sorting physical objects by attributes). Data collected via child drawings, teacher observation checklists, and child-led interviews (using picture cards). Qualitative analysis identifies skill patterns and teacher prompts that foster critical thinking without screens.  \n**DAP & Ethics:** Aligns with DAP by using *physical* tools to build foundational digital skills through concrete play, avoiding screen dependency. Ethical protocols include child-friendly consent (parental permission + child assent), no data storage